{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "IntroductionIn the dynamic landscape of natural language processing (NLP), the continual evolution of language models has fueled breakthroughs in understanding and generating human-like text [1].",
    "Intent classification and sentiment analysis are crucial tasks in natural language processing (NLP) with a wide range of applications, including dialogue systems, virtual assistants, and customer service chatbots.",
    "These tasks involve extracting meaningful information from textual data, such as identifying the user's intent behind a message or determining the overall sentiment expressed in a piece of text.",
    "As the demand for more sophisticated language understanding systems continues to grow, researchers and practitioners alike are faced with the task of optimizing existing models or adopting novel architectures to meet the evolving requirements of diverse applications.Encoder-only models, such as BERT (Bidirectional Encoder Representations from Transformers) [2] and its variant RoBERTa (Robustly optimized BERT approach) [3], have long been the mainstay for intent classification and sentiment analysis tasks.",
    "These models excel at learning contextual representations of words and sentences, enabling them to capture subtle semantic and syntactic information, making them well-suited for these tasks."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "IntroductionIn the dynamic landscape of natural language processing (NLP), the continual evolution of language models has fueled breakthroughs in understanding and generating human-like text [1].",
    "As the demand for more sophisticated language understanding systems continues to grow, researchers and practitioners alike are faced with the task of optimizing existing models or adopting novel architectures to meet the evolving requirements of diverse applications.Encoder-only models, such as BERT (Bidirectional Encoder Representations from Transformers) [2] and its variant RoBERTa (Robustly optimized BERT approach) [3], have long been the mainstay for intent classification and sentiment analysis tasks."
